# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: module-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] In mathematics, a **finitely generated module** is a module that has a finite generating set.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] A finitely generated module over a ring *R* may also be called a **finite *R*-module**, **finite over *R***, or a **module of finite type**.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Related concepts include **finitely cogenerated modules**, **finitely presented modules**, **finitely related modules** and **coherent modules** all of which are defined below.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Over a Noetherian ring the concepts of finitely generated, finitely presented and coherent modules coincide.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] A finitely generated module over a field is simply a finite-dimensional vector space, and a finitely generated module over the integers is simply a finitely generated abelian group.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] The set {*a*1, *a*2, ..., *a**n*} is referred to as a generating set of *M* in this case.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] A finite generating set need not be a basis, since it need not be linearly independent over *R*.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] for some *n*; in other words, *M* is a quotient of a free module of finite rank.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] If a set *S* generates a module that is finitely generated, then there is a finite generating set that is included in *S*, since only finitely many elements in *S* are needed to express the generators in any finite generating set, and these finitely many elements form a generating set.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] However, it may occur that *S* does not contain any finite generating set of minimal cardinality.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] For example the set of the prime numbers is a generating set of $\mathbb {Z}$ viewed as $\mathbb {Z}$ -module, and a generating set formed from prime numbers has at least two elements, while the singleton{1} is also a generating set.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Any module is the union of the directed set of its finitely generated submodules.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] A module *M* is finitely generated if and only if any increasing chain *M**i* of submodules with union *M* stabilizes: i.e., there is some *i* such that *M**i* = *M*.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] This fact with Zorn's lemma implies that every nonzero finitely generated module admits maximal submodules.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] If any increasing chain of submodules stabilizes (i.e., any submodule is finitely generated), then the module *M* is called a Noetherian module.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Every homomorphic image of a finitely generated module is finitely generated.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] In general, submodules of finitely generated modules need not be finitely generated.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] As an example, consider the ring *R* = **Z**[*X*1, *X*2, ...] of all polynomials in countably many variables.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] *R* itself is a finitely generated *R*-module (with {1} as generating set).
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Consider the submodule *K* consisting of all those polynomials with zero constant term.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Since every polynomial contains only finitely many terms whose coefficients are non-zero, the *R*-module *K* is not finitely generated.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] In general, a module is said to be Noetherian if every submodule is finitely generated.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] A finitely generated module over a Noetherian ring is a Noetherian module (and indeed this property characterizes Noetherian rings): A module over a Noetherian ring is finitely generated if and only if it is a Noetherian module.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] This resembles, but is not exactly Hilbert's basis theorem, which states that the polynomial ring *R*[*X*] over a Noetherian ring *R* is Noetherian.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Both facts imply that a finitely generated commutative algebra over a Noetherian ring is again a Noetherian ring.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] More generally, an algebra (e.g., ring) that is a finitely generated module is a finitely generated algebra.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Conversely, if a finitely generated algebra is integral (over the coefficient ring), then it is finitely generated module.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Let 0 → *M*′ → *M* → *M*′′ → 0 be an exact sequence of modules.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Then *M* is finitely generated if *M*′, *M*′′ are finitely generated.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] There are some partial converses to this.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] If *M* is finitely generated and *M*′′ is finitely presented (which is stronger than finitely generated; see below), then *M*′ is finitely generated.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Artinian) if and only if *M*′, *M*′′ are Noetherian (resp.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Let *B* be a ring and *A* its subring such that *B* is a faithfully flat right *A*-module.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Then a left *A*-module *F* is finitely generated (resp. finitely presented) if and only if the *B*-module *B* ⊗*A* *F* is finitely generated (resp. finitely presented).
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] For finitely generated modules over a commutative ring *R*, Nakayama's lemma is fundamental.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Sometimes, the lemma allows one to prove finite dimensional vector spaces phenomena for finitely generated modules.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] For example, if *f* : *M* → *M* is a surjective *R*-endomorphism of a finitely generated module *M*, then *f* is also injective, and hence is an automorphism of *M*.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] This says simply that *M* is a Hopfian module.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Similarly, an Artinian module *M* is coHopfian: any injective endomorphism *f* is also a surjective endomorphism.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] The Forster–Swan theorem gives an upper bound for the minimal number of generators of a finitely generated module *M* over a commutative Noetherian ring.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Any *R*-module is an inductive limit of finitely generated *R*-submodules.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] This is useful for weakening an assumption to the finite case (e.g., the characterization of flatness with the Tor functor).
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] An example of a link between finite generation and integral elements can be found in commutative algebras.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] To say that a commutative algebra *A* is a **finitely generated ring** over *R* means that there exists a set of elements *G* = {*x*1, ..., *x**n*} of *A* such that the smallest subring of *A* containing *G* and *R* is *A* itself.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Because the ring product may be used to combine elements, more than just *R*-linear combinations of elements of *G* are generated.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] For example, a polynomial ring *R*[*x*] is finitely generated by {1, *x*} as a ring, *but not as a module*.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Let *M* be a finitely generated module over an integral domain *A* with the field of fractions *K*.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Then the dimension $\operatorname {dim} _{K}(M\otimes _{A}K)$ is called the **generic rank** of *M* over *A*.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] This number is the same as the number of maximal *A*-linearly independent vectors in *M* or equivalently the rank of a maximal free submodule of *M* (*cf.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] When *A* is Noetherian, by generic freeness, there is an element *f* (depending on *M*) such that $M[f^{-1}]$ is a free $A[f^{-1}]$ -module.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Then the rank of this free module is the generic rank of *M*.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Now suppose the integral domain *A* is an $\mathbb {N}$ -graded algebra over a field *k* generated by finitely many homogeneous elements of degrees $d_{i}$ .
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Suppose *M* is graded as well and let $P_{M}(t)=\sum (\operatorname {dim} _{k}M_{n})t^{n}$ be the Poincaré series of *M*.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] A finitely generated module over a principal ideal domain is torsion-free if and only if it is free.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] This is a consequence of the structure theorem for finitely generated modules over a principal ideal domain, the basic form of which says a finitely generated module over a PID is a direct sum of a torsion module and a free module.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] But it can also be shown directly as follows: let *M* be a torsion-free finitely generated module over a PID *A* and *F* a maximal free submodule.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Let *f* be in *A* such that $fM\subset F$ .
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Then $fM$ is free since it is a submodule of a free module and *A* is a PID.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] But now $f:M\to fM$ is an isomorphism since *M* is torsion-free.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] By the same argument as above, a finitely generated module over a Dedekind domain *A* (or more generally a semi-hereditary ring) is torsion-free if and only if it is projective; consequently, a finitely generated module over *A* is a direct sum of a torsion module and a projective module.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] A finitely generated projective module over a Noetherian integral domain has constant rank and so the generic rank of a finitely generated module over *A* is the rank of its projective part.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] From these conditions it is easy to see that being finitely generated is a property preserved by Morita equivalence.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] The conditions are also convenient to define a dual notion of a **finitely cogenerated module** *M*.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Both f.g. modules and f.cog. modules have interesting relationships to Noetherian and Artinian modules, and the Jacobson radical *J*(*M*) and socle soc(*M*) of a module.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] The following facts illustrate the duality between the two conditions.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Finitely cogenerated modules must have finite uniform dimension.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] This is easily seen by applying the characterization using the finitely generated essential socle.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Somewhat asymmetrically, finitely generated modules *do not* necessarily have finite uniform dimension.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] For example, an infinite direct product of nonzero rings is a finitely generated (cyclic!) module over itself, however it clearly contains an infinite direct sum of nonzero submodules.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Finitely generated modules *do not* necessarily have finite co-uniform dimension either: any ring *R* with unity such that *R*/*J*(*R*) is not a semisimple ring is a counterexample.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Over any ring *R*, coherent modules are finitely presented, and finitely presented modules are both finitely generated and finitely related.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] For a Noetherian ring *R*, finitely generated, finitely presented, and coherent are equivalent conditions on a module.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Some crossover occurs for projective or flat modules.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] A finitely generated projective module is finitely presented, and a finitely related flat module is projective.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Every finitely presented right *R* module is coherent.
[src:module-theory/finitely-generated-module] Although coherence seems like a more cumbersome condition than finitely generated or finitely presented, it is nicer than them since the category of coherent modules is an abelian category, while, in general, neither finitely generated nor finitely presented modules form an abelian category.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] In algebra, **flat modules** include free modules, projective modules, and, over a principal ideal domain, torsion-free modules.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Formally, a module *M* over a ring *R* is *flat* if taking the tensor product over *R* with *M* preserves exact sequences.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] A module is **faithfully flat** if taking the tensor product with a sequence produces an exact sequence if and only if the original sequence is exact.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Flatness was introduced by Jean-Pierre Serre (1956) in his paper *Géometrie Algébrique et Géométrie Analytique*.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] For this definition, it is enough to restrict the injections $\varphi$ to the inclusions of finitely generated ideals into R.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] These definitions apply also if R is a non-commutative ring, and M is a left R-module; in this case, K, L and J must be right R-modules, and the tensor products are not R-modules in general, but only abelian groups.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Flatness can also be characterized by the following equational condition, which means that R-linear relations in M stem from linear relations in R.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] It is equivalent to define n elements of a module, and a linear map from $R^{n}$ to this module, which maps the standard basis of $R^{n}$ to the n elements.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] This allows rewriting the previous characterization in terms of homomorphisms, as follows.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Flatness is related to various other module properties, such as being free, projective, or torsion-free.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] In particular, every flat module is torsion-free, every projective module is flat, and every free module is projective.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] There are finitely generated modules that are flat and not projective.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] However, finitely generated flat modules are all projective over the rings that are most commonly considered.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Moreover, a finitely generated module is flat if and only it is locally free, meaning all the localizations at prime ideals are free modules.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] This is partly summarized in the following graphic.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] This results from the above characterization in terms of relations by taking *m* = 1.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] The converse holds over the integers, and more generally over principal ideal domains and Dedekind rings.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] An integral domain over which every torsion-free module is flat is called a Prüfer domain.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] A module M is projective if and only if there is a free module G and two linear maps $i:M\to G$ and $p:G\to M$ such that $p\circ i=\mathrm {id} _{M}.$ In particular, every free module is projective (take $G=M$ and $i=p=\mathrm {id} _{M}$ ).
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Conversely, finitely generated flat modules are projective under mild conditions that are generally satisfied in commutative algebra and algebraic geometry.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] This makes the concept of flatness useful mainly for modules that are not finitely generated.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] A finitely presented module (that is the quotient of a finitely generated free module by a finitely generated submodule) that is flat is always projective.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] This can be proven by taking f surjective and $K=\ker f$ in the above characterization of flatness in terms of linear maps.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] The condition $g(K)=0$ implies the existence of a linear map $i:M\to G$ such that $i\circ f=g,$ and thus $h\circ i\circ f=h\circ g=f.$ As f is surjective, one has thus $h\circ i=\mathrm {id} _{M},$ and M is projective.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Over a Noetherian ring, every finitely generated flat module is projective, since every finitely generated module is finitely presented.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] The same result is true over an integral domain, even if it is not Noetherian.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] On a local ring every finitely generated flat module is free.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] A finitely generated flat module that is not projective can be built as follows.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Let $R=F^{\mathbb {N} }$ be the set of the infinite sequences whose terms belong to a fixed field F.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] It is a commutative ring with addition and multiplication defined componentwise.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] This ring is absolutely flat (that is, every module is flat).
[src:module-theory/flat-module] The module $R/I,$ where I is the ideal of the sequences with a finite number of nonzero terms, is thus flat and finitely generated (only one generator), but it is not projective.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] The direct sum $\textstyle \bigoplus _{i\in I}M_{i}$ of modules is flat if and only if each $M_{i}$ is flat.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] The direct limit of flat modules is flat.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] In particular, the direct limit of free modules is flat.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Conversely, every flat module can be written as the direct limit of finitely-generated free modules.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Direct products of flat modules need not in general be flat.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] In fact, given a ring R, every direct product of flat R-modules is flat if and only if R is a coherent ring (that is, every finitely generated ideal is finitely presented).
[src:module-theory/flat-module] A ring homomorphism $R\to S$ is *flat* if S is a flat R-module for the module structure induced by the homomorphism.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] For example, the polynomial ring *R*[*t*] is flat over R, for any ring R.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] For any multiplicative subset S of a commutative ring R , the localization $S^{-1}R$ is a flat *R*-algebra (it is projective only in exceptional cases).
[src:module-theory/flat-module] If I is an ideal of a Noetherian commutative ring $R,$ the completion ${\widehat {R}}$ of R with respect to I is flat.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] In this section, R denotes a commutative ring.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] If ${\mathfrak {p}}$ is a prime ideal of R, the localization at ${\mathfrak {p}}$ is, as usual, denoted with ${\mathfrak {p}}$ as an index.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] This property is fundamental in commutative algebra and algebraic geometry, since it reduces the study of flatness to the case of local rings.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] They are often expressed by saying that flatness is a local property.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] The definition of a flat morphism of schemes results immediately from the local property of flatness.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] is a flat ring homomorphism for any point *x* in *X*.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Thus, properties of flat (or faithfully flat) ring homomorphisms extend naturally to geometric properties of flat morphisms in algebraic geometry.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] For example, consider the flat $\mathbb {C} [t]$ -algebra $R=\mathbb {C} [t,x,y]/(xy-t)$ (see below).
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Let $S=R[x_{1},\dots ,x_{r}]$ be a polynomial ring over a commutative Noetherian ring R and $f\in S$ a nonzerodivisor.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Then $S/fS$ is flat over R if and only if f is primitive (the coefficients generate the unit ideal).
[src:module-theory/flat-module] An example is $\mathbb {C} [t,x,y]/(xy-t),$ which is flat (and even free) over $\mathbb {C} [t]$ (see also below for the geometric meaning).
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Such flat extensions can be used to yield examples of flat modules that are not free and do not result from a localization.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] A module is *faithfully flat* if taking the tensor product with a sequence produces an exact sequence if and only if the original sequence is exact.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Although the concept is defined for modules over a non-necessary commutative ring, it is used mainly for commutative algebras.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] So, this is the only case that is considered here, even if some results can be generalized to the case of modules over a non-commutaive ring.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] In this section, $f\colon R\to S$ is a ring homomorphism of commutative rings, which gives to S the structures of an R -algebra and an R -module.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] If S is a R -module flat (or faithfully flat), one says commonly that S is flat (or faithfully flat) over $R,$ and that f is flat (or faithfully flat).
[src:module-theory/flat-module] If S is flat over $R,$ the following conditions are equivalent.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] The second condition implies that a flat local homomorphism of local rings is faithfully flat.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] It follows from the last condition that $I=IS\cap R$ for every ideal I of R (take $M=R/I$ ).
[src:module-theory/flat-module] In particular, if S is a Noetherian ring, then R is also Noetherian.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] See also *Flat morphism § Properties of flat morphisms*.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] The two last examples are implicitly behind the wide use of localization in commutative algebra and algebraic geometry.
