[src:module-theory/flat-module] Also, if B and C are flat, then so is A .
[src:module-theory/flat-module] If A and B are flat, C need not be flat in general.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] However, if A is pure in B and B is flat, then A and C are flat.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Any free or projective resolution is necessarily a flat resolution.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Flat resolutions can be used to compute the Tor functor.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] The *length* of a finite flat resolution is the first subscript *n* such that $F_{n}$ is nonzero and $F_{i}=0$ for $i>n$ .
[src:module-theory/flat-module] If a module M admits a finite flat resolution, the minimal length among all finite flat resolutions of M is called its flat dimension and denoted $\operatorname {fd} (M)$ .
[src:module-theory/flat-module] If M does not admit a finite flat resolution, then by convention the flat dimension is said to be infinite.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] As an example, consider a module M such that $\operatorname {fd} (M)=0$ .
[src:module-theory/flat-module] In this situation, the exactness of the sequence $0\to F_{0}\to M\to 0$ indicates that the arrow in the center is an isomorphism, and hence M itself is flat.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] In some areas of module theory, a flat resolution must satisfy the additional requirement that each map is a flat pre-cover of the kernel of the map to the right.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] For projective resolutions, this condition is almost invisible: a projective pre-cover is simply an epimorphism from a projective module.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] These ideas are inspired from Auslander's work in approximations.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] These ideas are also familiar from the more common notion of minimal projective resolutions, where each map is required to be a projective cover of the kernel of the map to the right.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] However, projective covers need not exist in general, so minimal projective resolutions are only of limited use over rings like the integers.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] This **flat cover conjecture** was explicitly first stated in Enochs (1981, p.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] The conjecture turned out to be true, resolved positively and proved simultaneously by L.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] This was preceded by important contributions by P.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Since flat covers exist for all modules over all rings, minimal flat resolutions can take the place of minimal projective resolutions in many circumstances.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] The measurement of the departure of flat resolutions from projective resolutions is called *relative homological algebra*, and is covered in classics such as Mac Lane (1963) and in more recent works focussing on flat resolutions such as Enochs and Jenda (2000).
[src:module-theory/flat-module] Flat modules have increased importance in constructive mathematics, where projective modules are less useful.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] For example, that all free modules are projective is equivalent to the full axiom of choice, so theorems about projective modules, even if proved constructively, do not necessarily apply to free modules.
[src:module-theory/flat-module] In contrast, no choice is needed to prove that free modules are flat, so theorems about flat modules can still apply.
[src:module-theory/free-module] In mathematics, a **free module** is a module that has a *basis*, that is, a generating set that is linearly independent.
[src:module-theory/free-module] Every vector space is a free module, but, if the ring of the coefficients is not a division ring (not a field in the commutative case), then there exist non-free modules.
[src:module-theory/free-module] Given any set *S* and ring *R*, there is a free *R*-module with basis *S*, which is called the *free module on* *S* or *module of formal* *R*-*linear combinations* of the elements of *S*.
[src:module-theory/free-module] A free abelian group is precisely a free module over the ring $\mathbb {Z}$ of integers.
[src:module-theory/free-module] An immediate consequence of the second half of the definition is that the coefficients in the first half are unique for each element of *M*.
[src:module-theory/free-module] If R has invariant basis number, then by definition any two bases have the same cardinality.
[src:module-theory/free-module] For example, nonzero commutative rings have invariant basis number.
[src:module-theory/free-module] The cardinality of any (and therefore every) basis is called the **rank** of the free module M .
[src:module-theory/free-module] If this cardinality is finite, the free module is said to be *free of finite rank*, or *free of rank* n if the rank is known to be n.
[src:module-theory/free-module] Explicitly, it is the submodule of the Cartesian product ${\textstyle \prod _{E}R}$ (*R* is viewed as say a left module) that consists of the elements that have only finitely many nonzero components.
