[src:module-theory/free-module] Many statements true for free modules extend to certain larger classes of modules.
[src:module-theory/free-module] Projective modules are direct summands of free modules.
[src:module-theory/free-module] Flat modules are defined by the property that tensoring with them preserves exact sequences.
[src:module-theory/free-module] Torsion-free modules form an even broader class.
[src:module-theory/free-module] For a finitely generated module over a PID (such as **Z**), the properties free, projective, flat, and torsion-free are equivalent.
[src:module-theory/free-module] See local ring, perfect ring and Dedekind ring.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] In mathematics, especially in the area of abstract algebra known as module theory, an **injective module** is a module *Q* that shares certain desirable properties with the **Z**-module **Q** of all rational numbers.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Specifically, if *Q* is a submodule of some other module, then it is already a direct summand of that module; also, given a submodule of a module *Y*, any module homomorphism from this submodule to *Q* can be extended to a homomorphism from all of *Y* to *Q*.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] This concept is dual to that of projective modules.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Injective modules were introduced in (Baer 1940) and are discussed in some detail in the textbook (Lam 1999, §3).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Injective modules have been heavily studied, and a variety of additional notions are defined in terms of them: Injective cogenerators are injective modules that faithfully represent the entire category of modules.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Injective resolutions measure how far from injective a module is in terms of the injective dimension and represent modules in the derived category.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Injective hulls are maximal essential extensions, and turn out to be minimal injective extensions.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Over a Noetherian ring, every injective module is uniquely a direct sum of indecomposable modules, and their structure is well understood.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] An injective module over one ring may be not injective over another, but there are well-understood methods of changing rings which handle special cases.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Rings which are themselves injective modules have a number of interesting properties and include rings such as group rings of finite groups over fields.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Injective modules include divisible groups and are generalized by the notion of injective objects in category theory.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Injective right R -modules are defined analogously.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Trivially, the zero module $\{0\}$ is injective.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Given a field k , every k -vector space Q is an injective k -module.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Reason: if Q is a subspace of V , we can find a basis of Q and extend it to a basis of V .
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The new extending basis vectors span a subspace K of V and V is the internal direct sum of Q and K .
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Note that the direct complement K of Q is not uniquely determined by Q , and likewise the extending map h in the above definition is typically not unique.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The rationals $\mathbb {Q}$ (with addition) form an injective abelian group (i.e. an injective $\mathbb {Z}$ -module).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The factor group $\mathbb {Q} /\mathbb {Z}$ and the circle group are also injective $\mathbb {Z}$ -modules.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The factor group $\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z}$ for $n>1$ is injective as a $\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z}$ -module, but *not* injective as an abelian group.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] More generally, for any integral domain *R* with field of fractions *K*, the *R*-module *K* is an injective *R*-module, and indeed the smallest injective *R*-module containing *R*.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] For any Dedekind domain, the quotient module *K*/*R* is also injective, and its indecomposable summands are the localizations $R_{\mathfrak {p}}/R$ for the nonzero prime ideals ${\mathfrak {p}}$ .
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The zero ideal is also prime and corresponds to the injective *K*.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] In this way there is a 1-1 correspondence between prime ideals and indecomposable injective modules.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] A particularly rich theory is available for commutative noetherian rings due to Eben Matlis, (Lam 1999, §3I).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Every injective module is uniquely a direct sum of indecomposable injective modules, and the indecomposable injective modules are uniquely identified as the injective hulls of the quotients *R*/*P* where *P* varies over the prime spectrum of the ring.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The injective hull of *R*/*P* as an *R*-module is canonically an *R**P* module, and is the *R**P*-injective hull of *R*/*P*.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] In other words, it suffices to consider local rings.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The endomorphism ring of the injective hull of *R*/*P* is the completion ${\hat {R}}_{P}$ of *R* at *P*.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Two examples are the injective hull of the **Z**-module **Z**/*p***Z** (the Prüfer group), and the injective hull of the *k*[*x*]-module *k* (the ring of inverse polynomials).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] This module has a basis consisting of "inverse monomials", that is *x*−*n* for *n* = 0, 1, 2, ….
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Multiplication by scalars is as expected, and multiplication by *x* behaves normally except that *x*·1 = 0.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The endomorphism ring is simply the ring of formal power series.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] If *G* is a finite group and *k* a field with characteristic 0, then one shows in the theory of group representations that any subrepresentation of a given one is already a direct summand of the given one.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Translated into module language, this means that all modules over the group algebra *kG* are injective.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] If the characteristic of *k* is not zero, the following example may help.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] If *A* is a unital associative algebra over the field *k* with finite dimension over *k*, then Hom*k*(−, *k*) is a duality between finitely generated left *A*-modules and finitely generated right *A*-modules.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Therefore, the finitely generated injective left *A*-modules are precisely the modules of the form Hom*k*(*P*, *k*) where *P* is a finitely generated projective right *A*-module.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] For symmetric algebras, the duality is particularly well-behaved and projective modules and injective modules coincide.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] For any Artinian ring, just as for commutative rings, there is a 1-1 correspondence between prime ideals and indecomposable injective modules.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The correspondence in this case is perhaps even simpler: a prime ideal is an annihilator of a unique simple module, and the corresponding indecomposable injective module is its injective hull.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] For finite-dimensional algebras over fields, these injective hulls are finitely-generated modules (Lam 1999, §3G, §3J).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] If R is a Noetherian ring and ${\mathfrak {p}}$ is a prime ideal, set $E=E(R/{\mathfrak {p}})$ as the injective hull.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The injective hull of $R/{\mathfrak {p}}$ over the Artinian ring $R/{\mathfrak {p}}^{k}$ can be computed as the module $(0:_{E}{\mathfrak {p}}^{k})$ .
[src:module-theory/injective-module] It is a module of the same length as $R/{\mathfrak {p}}^{k}$ .
[src:module-theory/injective-module] In particular, for the standard graded ring $R_{\bullet }=k[x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}]_{\bullet }$ and ${\mathfrak {p}}=(x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})$ , $E=\oplus _{i}{\text{Hom}}(R_{i},k)$ is an injective module, giving the tools for computing the indecomposable injective modules for artinian rings over k .
[src:module-theory/injective-module] An Artin local ring $(R,{\mathfrak {m}},K)$ is injective over itself if and only if $soc(R)$ is a 1-dimensional vector space over K .
[src:module-theory/injective-module] This implies every local Gorenstein ring which is also Artin is injective over itself since has a 1-dimensional socle.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] A simple non-example is the ring $R=\mathbb {C} [x,y]/(x^{2},xy,y^{2})$ which has maximal ideal $(x,y)$ and residue field $\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Its socle is $\mathbb {C} \cdot x\oplus \mathbb {C} \cdot y$ , which is 2-dimensional.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The residue field has the injective hull ${\text{Hom}}_{\mathbb {C} }(\mathbb {C} \cdot x\oplus \mathbb {C} \cdot y,\mathbb {C} )$ .
[src:module-theory/injective-module] For a Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ over a field k of characteristic 0, the category of modules ${\mathcal {M}}({\mathfrak {g}})$ has a relatively straightforward description of its injective modules.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] In fact, every ${\mathfrak {g}}$ -module has an injection into some ${\text{Hom}}_{k}(U({\mathfrak {g}}),V)$ and every injective ${\mathfrak {g}}$ -module is a direct summand of some ${\text{Hom}}_{k}(U({\mathfrak {g}}),V)$ .
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Over a commutative Noetherian ring R , every injective module is a direct sum of indecomposable injective modules and every indecomposable injective module is the injective hull of the residue field at a prime ${\mathfrak {p}}$ .
[src:module-theory/injective-module] where $E(R/{\mathfrak {p}}_{i})$ are the injective hulls of the modules $R/{\mathfrak {p}}_{i}$ .
[src:module-theory/injective-module] In addition, if I is the injective hull of some module M then the ${\mathfrak {p}}_{i}$ are the associated primes of M .
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Any product of (even infinitely many) injective modules is injective; conversely, if a direct product of modules is injective, then each module is injective (Lam 1999, p.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Every direct sum of finitely many injective modules is injective.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] In general, submodules, factor modules, or infinite direct sums of injective modules need not be injective.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Every submodule of every injective module is injective if and only if the ring is Artinian semisimple (Golan & Head 1991, p.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] 152); every factor module of every injective module is injective if and only if the ring is hereditary, (Lam 1999, Th.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Bass-Papp Theorem states that every infinite direct sum of right (left) injective modules is injective if and only if the ring is right (left) Noetherian, (Lam 1999, p.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] In Baer's original paper, he proved a useful result, usually known as Baer's Criterion, for checking whether a module is injective: a left *R*-module *Q* is injective if and only if any homomorphism *g* : *I* → *Q* defined on a left ideal *I* of *R* can be extended to all of *R*.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Using this criterion, one can show that **Q** is an injective abelian group (i.e. an injective module over **Z**).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] More generally, an abelian group is injective if and only if it is divisible.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] More generally still: a module over a principal ideal domain is injective if and only if it is divisible (the case of vector spaces is an example of this theorem, as every field is a principal ideal domain and every vector space is divisible).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Over a general integral domain, we still have one implication: every injective module over an integral domain is divisible.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Baer's criterion has been refined in many ways (Golan & Head 1991, p.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] 119), including a result of (Smith 1981) and (Vámos 1983) that for a commutative Noetherian ring, it suffices to consider only prime ideals *I*.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The dual of Baer's criterion, which would give a test for projectivity, is false in general.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] For instance, the **Z**-module **Q** satisfies the dual of Baer's criterion but is not projective.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Maybe the most important injective module is the abelian group **Q**/**Z**.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] It is an injective cogenerator in the category of abelian groups, which means that it is injective and any other module is contained in a suitably large product of copies of **Q**/**Z**.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] So in particular, every abelian group is a subgroup of an injective one.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] For a left *R*-module *M*, the so-called "character module" *M*+ = Hom**Z**(*M*,**Q**/**Z**) is a right *R*-module that exhibits an interesting duality, not between injective modules and projective modules, but between injective modules and flat modules (Enochs & Jenda 2000, pp.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] For any ring *R*, a left *R*-module is flat if and only if its character module is injective.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] If *R* is left noetherian, then a left *R*-module is injective if and only if its character module is flat.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The injective hull of a module is the smallest injective module containing the given one and was described in (Eckmann & Schopf 1953).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] One can use injective hulls to define a minimal injective resolution (see below).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] If each term of the injective resolution is the injective hull of the cokernel of the previous map, then the injective resolution has minimal length.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] where the *I* *j* are injective modules.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Injective resolutions can be used to define derived functors such as the Ext functor.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The *length* of a finite injective resolution is the first index *n* such that *I**n* is nonzero and *I**i* = 0 for *i* greater than *n*.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] If a module *M* admits a finite injective resolution, the minimal length among all finite injective resolutions of *M* is called its injective dimension and denoted id(*M*).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] If *M* does not admit a finite injective resolution, then by convention the injective dimension is said to be infinite.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] (Lam 1999, §5C) As an example, consider a module *M* such that id(*M*) = 0.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] In this situation, the exactness of the sequence 0 → *M* → *I*0 → 0 indicates that the arrow in the center is an isomorphism, and hence *M* itself is injective.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Equivalently, the injective dimension of *M* is the minimal integer (if there is such, otherwise ∞) *n* such that Ext*N* *A*(–,*M*) = 0 for all *N* > *n*.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Every injective submodule of an injective module is a direct summand, so it is important to understand indecomposable injective modules, (Lam 1999, §3F).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Every indecomposable injective module has a local endomorphism ring.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] A module is called a *uniform module* if every two nonzero submodules have nonzero intersection.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Over a Noetherian ring, every injective module is the direct sum of (uniquely determined) indecomposable injective modules.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Over a commutative Noetherian ring, this gives a particularly nice understanding of all injective modules, described in (Matlis 1958).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The indecomposable injective modules are the injective hulls of the modules *R*/*p* for *p* a prime ideal of the ring *R*.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Moreover, the injective hull *M* of *R*/*p* has an increasing filtration by modules *M**n* given by the annihilators of the ideals *p**n*, and *M**n*+1/*M**n* is isomorphic as finite-dimensional vector space over the quotient field *k*(*p*) of *R*/*p* to Hom*R*/*p*(*p**n*/*p**n*+1, *k*(*p*)).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] It is important to be able to consider modules over subrings or quotient rings, especially for instance polynomial rings.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] In general, this is difficult, but a number of results are known, (Lam 1999, p.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Let *S* and *R* be rings, and *P* be a left-*R*, right-*S* bimodule that is flat as a left-*R* module.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] For any injective right *S*-module *M*, the set of module homomorphisms Hom*S*( *P*, *M* ) is an injective right *R*-module.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The same statement holds of course after interchanging left- and right- attributes.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] For instance, if *R* is a subring of *S* such that *S* is a flat *R*-module, then every injective *S*-module is an injective *R*-module.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] In particular, if *R* is an integral domain and *S* its field of fractions, then every vector space over *S* is an injective *R*-module.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Similarly, every injective *R*[*x*]-module is an injective *R*-module.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] In the opposite direction, a ring homomorphism $f:S\to R$ makes *R* into a left-*R*, right-*S* bimodule, by left and right multiplication.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Being free over itself *R* is also flat as a left *R*-module.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Specializing the above statement for *P = R*, it says that when *M* is an injective right *S*-module the coinduced module $f_{*}M=\mathrm {Hom} _{S}(R,M)$ is an injective right *R*-module.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Thus, coinduction over *f* produces injective *R*-modules from injective *S*-modules.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] For quotient rings *R*/*I*, the change of rings is also very clear.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] An *R*-module is an *R*/*I*-module precisely when it is annihilated by *I*.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The submodule ann*I*(*M*) = { *m* in *M* : *im* = 0 for all *i* in *I* } is a left submodule of the left *R*-module *M*, and is the largest submodule of *M* that is an *R*/*I*-module.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] If *M* is an injective left *R*-module, then ann*I*(*M*) is an injective left *R*/*I*-module.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] While it is easy to convert injective *R*-modules into injective *R*/*I*-modules, this process does not convert injective *R*-resolutions into injective *R*/*I*-resolutions, and the homology of the resulting complex is one of the early and fundamental areas of study of relative homological algebra.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] 103) has an erroneous proof that localization preserves injectives, but a counterexample was given in (Dade 1981).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Every ring with unity is a free module and hence is a projective as a module over itself, but it is rarer for a ring to be injective as a module over itself, (Lam 1999, §3B).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] If a ring is injective over itself as a right module, then it is called a right self-injective ring.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Every Frobenius algebra is self-injective, but no integral domain that is not a field is self-injective.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Every proper quotient of a Dedekind domain is self-injective.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] A right Noetherian, right self-injective ring is called a quasi-Frobenius ring, and is two-sided Artinian and two-sided injective, (Lam 1999, Th.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] An important module theoretic property of quasi-Frobenius rings is that the projective modules are exactly the injective modules.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] One also talks about injective objects in categories more general than module categories, for instance in functor categories or in categories of sheaves of O*X*-modules over some ringed space (*X*,O*X*).
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The following general definition is used: an object *Q* of the category *C* is injective if for any monomorphism *f* : *X* → *Y* in *C* and any morphism *g* : *X* → *Q* there exists a morphism *h* : *Y* → *Q* with *hf* = *g*.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] The notion of injective object in the category of abelian groups was studied somewhat independently of injective modules under the term divisible group.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Here a **Z**-module *M* is injective if and only if *n*⋅*M* = *M* for every nonzero integer *n*.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] Here the relationships between flat modules, pure submodules, and injective modules is more clear, as it simply refers to certain divisibility properties of module elements by integers.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] In relative homological algebra, the extension property of homomorphisms may be required only for certain submodules, rather than for all.
[src:module-theory/injective-module] For instance, a pure injective module is a module in which a homomorphism from a pure submodule can be extended to the whole module.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] In mathematics, a **module** is a generalization of the notion of vector space in which the field of scalars is replaced by a (not necessarily commutative) ring.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] The concept of a *module* also generalizes the notion of an abelian group, since the abelian groups are exactly the modules over the ring of integers.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Like a vector space, a module is an additive abelian group, and scalar multiplication is distributive over the operations of addition between elements of the ring or module and is compatible with the ring multiplication.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Modules are very closely related to the representation theory of groups.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] They are also one of the central notions of commutative algebra and homological algebra, and are used widely in algebraic geometry and algebraic topology.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] In a vector space, the set of scalars is a field and acts on the vectors by scalar multiplication, subject to certain axioms such as the distributive law.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] In a module, the scalars need only be a ring, so the module concept represents a significant generalization.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] In commutative algebra, both ideals and quotient rings are modules, so that many arguments about ideals or quotient rings can be combined into a single argument about modules.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] In non-commutative algebra, the distinction between left ideals, ideals, and modules becomes more pronounced, though some ring-theoretic conditions can be expressed either about left ideals or left modules.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Much of the theory of modules consists of extending as many of the desirable properties of vector spaces as possible to the realm of modules over a "well-behaved" ring, such as a principal ideal domain.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Suppose that *R* is a ring, and 1 is its multiplicative identity.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] The operation · is called *scalar multiplication*.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Often the symbol · is omitted, but in this article we use it and reserve juxtaposition for multiplication in *R*.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] One may write *R**M* to emphasize that *M* is a left *R*-module.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] A **right *R*-module** *M**R* is defined similarly in terms of an operation · : *M* × *R* → *M*.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] one gets a right-module, even if the scalars are written on the left.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] However, writing the scalars on the left for left-modules and on the right for right modules makes the manipulation of property 3 much easier.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Authors who do not require rings to be unital omit condition 4 in the definition above; they would call the structures defined above "unital left *R*-modules".
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] In this article, consistent with the glossary of ring theory, all rings and modules are assumed to be unital.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] If *R* is commutative, then left *R*-modules are the same as right *R*-modules and are simply called *R*-modules.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Most often the scalars are written on the left in this case.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Suppose *M* is a left *R*-module and *N* is a subgroup of *M*.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Then *N* is a **submodule** (or more explicitly an *R*-submodule) if for any *n* in *N* and any *r* in *R*, the product *r* ⋅ *n* (or *n* ⋅ *r* for a right *R*-module) is in *N*.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] This, like any homomorphism of mathematical objects, is just a mapping that preserves the structure of the objects.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Another name for a homomorphism of *R*-modules is an *R*-linear map.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] A bijective module homomorphism *f* : *M* → *N* is called a module isomorphism, and the two modules *M* and *N* are called **isomorphic**.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Two isomorphic modules are identical for all practical purposes, differing solely in the notation for their elements.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] The kernel of a module homomorphism *f* : *M* → *N* is the submodule of *M* consisting of all elements that are sent to zero by *f*, and the image of *f* is the submodule of *N* consisting of values *f*(*m*) for all elements *m* of *M*.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] The isomorphism theorems familiar from groups and vector spaces are also valid for *R*-modules.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Given a ring *R*, the set of all left *R*-modules together with their module homomorphisms forms an abelian category, denoted by *R*-**Mod** (see category of modules).
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] These are the modules that behave very much like vector spaces.
