[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] A representation of a group *G* over a field *k* is a module over the group ring *k*[*G*].
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] If *M* is a left *R*-module, then the *action* of an element *r* in *R* is defined to be the map *M* → *M* that sends each *x* to *rx* (or *xr* in the case of a right module), and is necessarily a group endomorphism of the abelian group (*M*, +).
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] The set of all group endomorphisms of *M* is denoted End**Z**(*M*) and forms a ring under addition and composition, and sending a ring element *r* of *R* to its action actually defines a ring homomorphism from *R* to End**Z**(*M*).
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Such a ring homomorphism *R* → End**Z**(*M*) is called a *representation* of the abelian group *M* over the ring *R*; an alternative and equivalent way of defining left *R*-modules is to say that a left *R*-module is an abelian group *M* together with a representation of *M* over *R*.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Such a representation *R* → End**Z**(*M*) may also be called a *ring action* of *R* on *M*.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] A representation is called *faithful* if the map *R* → End**Z**(*M*) is injective.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] In terms of modules, this means that if *r* is an element of *R* such that *rx* = 0 for all *x* in *M*, then *r* = 0.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Every abelian group is a faithful module over the integers or over the ring of integers modulo *n*, **Z**/*n***Z**, for some *n*.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] A ring *R* corresponds to a preadditive category **R** with a single object.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] With this understanding, a left *R*-module is just a covariant additive functor from **R** to the category of abelian groups **Ab**, and right *R*-modules are contravariant additive functors.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] This suggests that, if **C** is any preadditive category, a covariant additive functor from **C** to **Ab** should be considered a generalized left module over **C**.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] These functors form a functor category **C**-**Mod**, which is the natural generalization of the module category *R*-**Mod**.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Modules over *commutative* rings can be generalized in a different direction: take a ringed space (*X*, O*X*) and consider the sheaves of O*X*-modules (see sheaf of modules).
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] These form a category O*X*-**Mod**, and play an important role in modern algebraic geometry.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] If *X* has only a single point, then this is a module category in the old sense over the commutative ring O*X*(*X*).
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] One can also consider modules over a semiring, called a semimodule.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Modules over rings are abelian groups, but modules over semirings are only commutative monoids.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Most applications of modules are still possible.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] In particular, for any semiring *S*, the matrices over *S* form a semiring over which the tuples of elements from *S* are a module (in this generalized sense only).
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] This allows a further generalization of the concept of vector space incorporating the semirings from theoretical computer science.
[src:module-theory/module-mathematics] Over near-rings, one can consider near-ring modules, a nonabelian generalization of modules.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] In mathematics, particularly in algebra, the class of **projective modules** enlarges the class of free modules (that is, modules with basis vectors) over a ring, keeping some of the main properties of free modules.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Various equivalent characterizations of these modules appear below.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Every free module is a projective module, but the converse fails to hold over some rings, such as Dedekind rings that are not principal ideal domains.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] However, every projective module is a free module if the ring is a principal ideal domain such as the integers, or a (multivariate) polynomial ring over a field (this is the Quillen–Suslin theorem).
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Projective modules were first introduced in 1956 in the influential book *Homological Algebra* by Henri Cartan and Samuel Eilenberg.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] The advantage of this definition of "projective" is that it can be carried out in categories more general than module categories: we don't need a notion of "free object".
[src:module-theory/projective-module] It can also be dualized, leading to injective modules.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] The lifting property may also be rephrased as *every morphism from P to M factors through every epimorphism to M*.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Thus, by definition, projective modules are precisely the projective objects in the category of *R*-modules.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] That is, for every surjective module homomorphism *f* : *B* ↠ *P* there exists a **section map**, that is, a module homomorphism *h* : *P* → *B* such that *fh* = id*P*.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] In that case, *h*(*P*) is a direct summand of *B*, *h* is an isomorphism from *P* to *h*(*P*), and *hf* is a projection on the summand *h*(*P*).
[src:module-theory/projective-module] A module *P* is projective if and only if there is another module *Q* such that the direct sum of *P* and *Q* is a free module.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] An *R*-module *P* is projective if and only if the covariant functor Hom(*P*, -): *R*-**Mod** → **Ab** is an exact functor, where *R*-**Mod** is the category of left *R*-modules and **Ab** is the category of abelian groups.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] When the ring *R* is commutative, **Ab** is advantageously replaced by *R*-**Mod** in the preceding characterization.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] This functor is always left exact, but, when *P* is projective, it is also right exact.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] This means that *P* is projective if and only if this functor preserves epimorphisms (surjective homomorphisms), or if it preserves finite colimits.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] A module *P* is projective if and only if there exists a set $\{a_{i}\in P\mid i\in I\}$ and a set $\{f_{i}\in \mathrm {Hom} (P,R)\mid i\in I\}$ such that for every *x* in *P*, *f**i*(*x*) is only nonzero for finitely many *i*, and $x=\sum f_{i}(x)a_{i}$ .
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Let $R=R_{1}\times R_{2}$ be the direct product of two rings $R_{1}$ and $R_{2},$ which is a ring with operations defined componentwise.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Let $e_{1}=(1,0)$ and $e_{2}=(0,1).$ Then $e_{1}$ and $e_{2}$ are idempotents, and belong to the centre of $R.$ The two-sided ideals $Re_{1}$ and $Re_{2}$ are projective modules, since their direct sum (as R-modules) equals the free R-module R.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] However, if $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$ are nontrivial, then they are not free as modules over R .
[src:module-theory/projective-module] For instance $\mathbb {Z} /2\mathbb {Z}$ is projective but not free over $\mathbb {Z} /6\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:module-theory/projective-module] The left-to-right implications are true over any ring, although some authors define torsion-free modules only over a domain.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] The right-to-left implications are true over the rings labeling them.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] There may be other rings over which they are true.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] For example, the implication labeled "local ring or PID" is also true for (multivariate) polynomial rings over a field: this is the Quillen–Suslin theorem.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] The difference between free and projective modules is, in a sense, measured by the algebraic *K*-theory group *K*0(*R*); see below.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] The converse is in general not true: the abelian group **Q** is a **Z**-module that is flat, but not projective.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Conversely, a finitely related flat module is projective.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Govorov (1965) and Lazard (1969) proved that a module *M* is flat if and only if it is a direct limit of finitely-generated free modules.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] This characterization can be used to show that if $R\to S$ is a faithfully flat map of commutative rings and M is an R -module, then M is projective if and only if $M\otimes _{R}S$ is projective.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] In other words, the property of being projective satisfies faithfully flat descent.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Submodules of projective modules need not be projective; a ring *R* for which every submodule of a projective left module is projective is called left hereditary.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Quotients of projective modules also need not be projective, for example **Z**/*n* is a quotient of **Z**, but not torsion-free, hence not flat, and therefore not projective.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] The category of finitely generated projective modules over a ring is an exact category.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Every module possesses a projective resolution.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] In fact a **free resolution** (resolution by free modules) exists.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] The exact sequence of projective modules may sometimes be abbreviated to *P*(*M*) → *M* → 0 or *P*• → *M* → 0.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] A classic example of a projective resolution is given by the Koszul complex of a regular sequence, which is a free resolution of the ideal generated by the sequence.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] The *length* of a finite resolution is the index *n* such that *P**n* is nonzero and *P**i* = 0 for *i* greater than *n*.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] If *M* admits a finite projective resolution, the minimal length among all finite projective resolutions of *M* is called its **projective dimension** and denoted pd(*M*).
[src:module-theory/projective-module] If *M* does not admit a finite projective resolution, then by convention the projective dimension is said to be infinite.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] As an example, consider a module *M* such that pd(*M*) = 0.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] In this situation, the exactness of the sequence 0 → *P*0 → *M* → 0 indicates that the arrow in the center is an isomorphism, and hence *M* itself is projective.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Projective modules over commutative rings have nice properties.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] The localization of a projective module is a projective module over the localized ring.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] A projective module over a local ring is free.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Thus a projective module is *locally free* (in the sense that its localization at every prime ideal is free over the corresponding localization of the ring).
[src:module-theory/projective-module] The converse is true for finitely generated modules over Noetherian rings: a finitely generated module over a commutative Noetherian ring is locally free if and only if it is projective.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] However, there are examples of finitely generated modules over a non-Noetherian ring that are locally free and not projective.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] For instance, a Boolean ring has all of its localizations isomorphic to **F**2, the field of two elements, so any module over a Boolean ring is locally free, but there are some non-projective modules over Boolean rings.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] One example is *R*/*I* where *R* is a direct product of countably many copies of **F**2 and *I* is the direct sum of countably many copies of **F**2 inside of *R*.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] The *R*-module *R*/*I* is locally free since *R* is Boolean (and it is finitely generated as an *R*-module too, with a spanning set of size 1), but *R*/*I* is not projective because *I* is not a principal ideal.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] However, it is true that for finitely presented modules *M* over a commutative ring *R* (in particular if *M* is a finitely generated *R*-module and *R* is Noetherian), the following are equivalent.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] 3. $M_{\mathfrak {m}}$ is free as $R_{\mathfrak {m}}$ -module for every maximal ideal ${\mathfrak {m}}$ of *R*.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] 4. $M_{\mathfrak {p}}$ is free as $R_{\mathfrak {p}}$ -module for every prime ideal ${\mathfrak {p}}$ of *R*.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] If *B* is a (possibly non-commutative) *A*-algebra that is a finitely generated projective *A*-module containing *A* as a subring, then *A* is a direct factor of *B*.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Let *P* be a finitely generated projective module over a commutative ring *R* and *X* be the spectrum of *R*.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] The *rank* of *P* at a prime ideal ${\mathfrak {p}}$ in *X* is the rank of the free $R_{\mathfrak {p}}$ -module $P_{\mathfrak {p}}$ .
[src:module-theory/projective-module] It is a locally constant function on *X*.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] In particular, if *X* is connected (that is if *R* has no other idempotents than 0 and 1), then *P* has constant rank.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] A basic motivation of the theory is that projective modules (at least over certain commutative rings) are analogues of vector bundles.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] If there is some notion of "localization" that can be carried over to modules, such as the usual localization of a ring, one can define locally free modules, and the projective modules then typically coincide with the locally free modules.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] The Quillen–Suslin theorem, which solves Serre's problem, is another deep result: if *K* is a field, or more generally a principal ideal domain, and *R* = *K*[*X*1,...,*X**n*] is a polynomial ring over *K*, then every projective module over *R* is free.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] This problem was first raised by Serre with *K* a field (and the modules being finitely generated).
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Bass settled it for non-finitely generated modules, and Quillen and Suslin independently and simultaneously treated the case of finitely generated modules.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Since every projective module over a principal ideal domain is free, one might ask this question: if *R* is a commutative ring such that every (finitely generated) projective *R*-module is free, then is every (finitely generated) projective *R*[*X*]-module free?
[src:module-theory/projective-module] A counterexample occurs with *R* equal to the local ring of the curve *y*2 = *x*3 at the origin.
[src:module-theory/projective-module] Thus the Quillen–Suslin theorem could never be proved by a simple induction on the number of variables.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] In mathematics, the **tensor product of modules** is a construction that allows arguments about bilinear maps (e.g. multiplication) to be carried out in terms of linear maps.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] The module construction is analogous to the construction of the tensor product of vector spaces, but can be carried out for a pair of modules over a commutative ring resulting in a third module, and also for a pair of a right-module and a left-module over any ring, with result an abelian group.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] Tensor products are important in areas of abstract algebra, homological algebra, algebraic topology, algebraic geometry, operator algebras and noncommutative geometry.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] The universal property of the tensor product of vector spaces extends to more general situations in abstract algebra.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] The tensor product of an algebra and a module can be used for extension of scalars.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] For a commutative ring, the tensor product of modules can be iterated to form the tensor algebra of a module, allowing one to define multiplication in the module in a universal way.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] The set of all such balanced products over *R* from *M* × *N* to *G* is denoted by L*R*(*M*, *N*; *G*).
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] If *φ*, *ψ* are balanced products, then each of the operations *φ* + *ψ* and −*φ* defined pointwise is a balanced product.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] This turns the set L*R*(*M*, *N*; *G*) into an abelian group.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] For *M* and *N* fixed, the map *G* ↦ L*R*(*M*, *N*; *G*) is a functor from the category of abelian groups to itself.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] The morphism part is given by mapping a group homomorphism *g* : *G* → *G*′ to the function *φ* ↦ *g* ∘ *φ*, which goes from L*R*(*M*, *N*; *G*) to L*R*(*M*, *N*; *G*′).
