[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] The direct product of *M* and *N* is rarely isomorphic to the tensor product of *M* and *N*.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] When *R* is not commutative, then the tensor product requires that *M* and *N* be modules on opposite sides, while the direct product requires they be modules on the same side.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] In all cases the only function from *M* × *N* to *G* that is both linear and bilinear is the zero map.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] In the general case, not all the properties of a tensor product of vector spaces extend to modules.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] Yet, some useful properties of the tensor product, considered as module homomorphisms, remain.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] The **dual module** of a right *R*-module *E*, is defined as Hom*R*(*E*, *R*) with the canonical left *R*-module structure, and is denoted *E*∗.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] The canonical structure is the pointwise operations of addition and scalar multiplication.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] There is always a canonical homomorphism *E* → *E*∗∗ from *E* to its second dual.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] It is an isomorphism if *E* is a free module of finite rank.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] In general, *E* is called a reflexive module if the canonical homomorphism is an isomorphism.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] In the general case, each element of the tensor product of modules gives rise to a left *R*-linear map, to a right *R*-linear map, and to an *R*-bilinear form.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] Unlike in the commutative case, in the general case the tensor product is not an *R*-module, and thus does not support scalar multiplication.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] Both cases hold for general modules, and the homomorphisms are isomorphisms if the modules *E* and *F* are finitely generated projective modules (in particular, free modules of finite ranks).
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] Thus, an element of the tensor product of modules over a ring *R* maps canonically onto an *R*-linear map, though as with vector spaces, constraints apply to the modules for this to be equivalent to the full space of such linear maps.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] Let *R* be a commutative ring and *E* an *R*-module.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] Then there is a canonical *R*-linear map: $E^{*}\otimes _{R}E\to R$ induced through linearity by ⁠ $\phi \otimes x\mapsto \phi (x)$ ⁠; it is the unique *R*-linear map corresponding to the natural pairing.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] When *R* is a field, this is the usual trace of a linear transformation.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] The most prominent example of a tensor product of modules in differential geometry is the tensor product of the spaces of vector fields and differential forms.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] By definition, an element of ${\mathfrak {T}}_{q}^{p}$ is a tensor field of type (*p*, *q*).
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] It is called the contraction of tensors in the index (*k*, *l*).
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] In general, $-\otimes _{R}-:{\text{Mod-}}R\times R{\text{-Mod}}\longrightarrow \mathrm {Ab}$ is a bifunctor which accepts a right and a left *R* module pair as input, and assigns them to the tensor product in the category of abelian groups.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] Unlike the Hom bifunctor $\mathrm {Hom} _{R}(-,-),$ the tensor functor is covariant in both inputs.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] By definition, a module *T* is a flat module if $T\otimes _{R}-$ is an exact functor.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] If *M* is a flat module, the functor $M\otimes _{R}-$ is exact by the very definition of a flat module.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] If the tensor products are taken over a field *F*, we are in the case of vector spaces as above.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] Since all *F* modules are flat, the bifunctor $-\otimes _{R}-$ is exact in both positions, and the two given generating sets are bases, then $\{m_{i}\otimes n_{j}\mid i\in I,j\in J\}$ indeed forms a basis for ⁠ $M\otimes _{F}N$ ⁠.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] If *S* and *T* are commutative *R*-algebras, then, similar to #For equivalent modules, *S* ⊗*R* *T* will be a commutative *R*-algebra as well, with the multiplication map defined by (*m*1 ⊗ *m*2) (*n*1 ⊗ *n*2) = (*m*1*n*1 ⊗ *m*2*n*2) and extended by linearity.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] In this setting, the tensor product become a fibered coproduct in the category of commutative *R*-algebras.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] If *M* and *N* are both *R*-modules over a commutative ring, then their tensor product is again an *R*-module.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] The action of *R* on *M* factors through an action of a quotient commutative ring.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] In this case the tensor product of *M* with itself over *R* is again an *R*-module.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] This is a very common technique in commutative algebra.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] For example, if *C* is a chain complex of flat abelian groups and if *G* is an abelian group, then the homology group of $C\otimes _{\mathbb {Z} }G$ is the homology group of *C* with coefficients in *G* (see also: universal coefficient theorem).
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] The tensor product of sheaves of modules is the sheaf associated to the pre-sheaf of the tensor products of the modules of sections over open subsets.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] The **exterior bundle** on *M* is the subbundle of the tensor bundle consisting of all antisymmetric covariant tensors.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] Sections of the exterior bundle are differential forms on *M*.
[src:module-theory/tensor-product-of-modules] One important case when one forms a tensor product over a sheaf of non-commutative rings appears in theory of *D*-modules; that is, tensor products over the sheaf of differential operators.
